[2] China - (Anhui) death
Date: Thu 29 Mar 2007
From: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/SP133545.htm>

China: Update on human bird flu death in Anhui
-----------------------------------------------
A teenage boy has died after falling ill with the bird flu virus,
Chinese state media reported on Thursday [29 Mar 2007], confirming
the country's 3rd case of human infection from the virus so far this
year [2007].
The 16-year-old student from Bengbu in eastern China's rural Anhui
province died late on Tuesday [27 Mar 2007], the Xinhua news agency
reported, citing a provincial health official. The boy was admitted
to hospital on 18 Mar 2007 after falling ill with a fever and signs
of pneumonia.
Tests by China's Centre for Disease Control and Prevention confirmed
he had H5N1, which can spread from birds to humans through close
contact. But health authorities appeared to have little idea how the
boy came into contact with the virus. Initial investigations failed
to reveal that the boy had any "history of exposure to fowl that died
because of illness," Xinhua reported. Animal health experts have also
failed to find signs of the virus among birds in the area.
The World Health Organization has been notified of the death as has
Hong Kong and some other governments, the report said. China has now
reported a total of 24 human cases of H5N1, including 15 deaths,
since 2003. The virus has spread to more than 50 countries, raising
experts' fears it could mutate into a form that can easily pass from
person to person, risking a pandemic. China, with the world's largest
poultry population and millions of backyard birds roaming free, is
seen as key to the fight against bird flu.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D
Chief Scientist,
EAI Corporation
Research Associate,
Institute of Arctic Biology - University of Alaska Fairbanks
Department of Earth Science - University of Alaska Museum
<fnjpd@uaf.edu>
[Since October 2005, human cases of H5N1 avian influenza have been
reported from the provinces of Anhui, Guangxi, Liaoning, Jiangxi,
Fujian, Hunan, Sichuan, Guangdong, Shanghai, Hubei, and Xinjiang
Uygur. A farmer in the eastern province of Anhui was diagnosed
H5N1-positive as recently as January 2007. A map of the provinces of
China can be accessed at
<http://www.chinakontor.de/chinamap2.jpg>.
- Mod.CP]
