[3] Indonesia (East Java) - 64th (?) death
Date: Wed 28 Mar 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Antara News online [edited]
<http://www.antara.co.id/en/arc/2007/3/28/bird-flu-patient-dies-at-dr-soetomo-hospital-surabaya/>

Indonesia: Bird flu patient dies at Dr. Soetomo hospital, Surabaya
-----------------------------------------------
A 39-year-old bird flu patient at Dr. Soetomo Hospital here [died]
early Wednesday [28 Mar 2007] morning after having been treated for
several days. Hospital spokesman Dr. Teguh Sylvaranto said the woman,
a resident of Jetis village in Mojokerto district, East Java died of
H5N1 virus-induced liver and kidney failure. He said her body had
been handed to the family members for burial in Mojokerto.
According to Dr. Teguh Sylvaranto, she was the 2nd bird flu patient
who died at Dr. Soetomo Hospital, after the death of another patient,
also from Mojokerto, a week earlier. He pointed out that of 11 bird
flu suspects who had been treated in the hospital, 4 tested
H5N1-positive, and the remainder tested negative.
There are at least 81 confirmed human cases of bird flu in Indonesia,
with 64 of them fatal. Data from the World Health Organization (WHO)
said there were 274 confirmed human cases of avian influenza A virus
infection worldwide, 167 of whom were fatal. [As of 28 Mar 2007, the
WHO lists 284 human cases of avian H5N1 influenza and 169 deaths
worldwide and the total number of fatalities in Indonesia as 63.
Presumably, the East Java case described in this report may be the
64th fatality. - Mod.CP]
Meanwhile, Indonesia agreed on Tuesday [27 Mar 2007] to resume
sending bird flu samples to laboratories overseas after a 2-day
meeting on the issue organized by WHO. Health Minister Siti Fadillah
Supari was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying Indonesia expected a
guarantee that the samples would not be used to develop commercial
bird flu vaccines.
"We will resume sharing bird flu samples with the World Health
Organization immediately," the health minister said.
